How to capture RAINDROPS!💧🤯

We’ve all seen them, those wonderful cinematic rain shots: perfect drops caught in slow-motion🔥. It seems like these professional looking shots are too hard to recreate. However, you can achieve it with only a simple trick😱. What you need isn’t much: just your smartphone and some rain drops💥.

Step-by-Step Tutorial:

1️⃣Set your phone to slowmotion

👉In the camera app, select slowmotion mode.

2️⃣ Set the focus

👉Put your hand in front of the lens and hold your finger on the screen. Now, your smartphone will only focus on objects close to your camera lens🔘. 

3️⃣ Wait for the perfect drop

👉Take your smartphone where the drops will fall and start following the rain drops. Most of the time, the first take won’t be the best. So retake until you’re satisfied!✅
—————————————
🎥| @thecreatingwonders

Step-by-Step Tutorial:

1️⃣ Take a photo
2️⃣ Take a photo of your smartphone at the same angle
2️⃣ Open the app ‘PicsArt’
3️⃣ Import the photo of your smartphone
4️⃣ Add the first image (Toolbar > ‘Add Photo’ > click the image)
5️⃣ Scale the image and put the opacity to 100%
6️⃣ Click the third icon (on top) and select ‘Erase’ (Toolbar > ‘Erase’)
7️⃣ Erase the screen and mask out your subject

Did you know that you can use panorama mode to capture really tall objects?✨ This is useful when you can’t get far enough away from the object, or when you don’t want everything else in the frame.🔥

To begin, select Panorama Mode. Next, turn your smartphone sideways, press the shutter button and follow the line pointing up. The secret of taking panorama photos, is to move slowly and smoothly. There is a line in the middle of your screen with an arrow which directs you. Keeping the arrow on the line is basically the challenge of this trick. However, don’t worry if you stray from the line.
When you’ve captured whatever you wanted, hit the shutter again.✅

Video editing tutorial!✨ In this tutorial, the app ‘InShot’ is being used. The app is available in the Google Play Store and the App Store.

If you want to recreate this video, you’ll need: 8 videos, 21 photos and a black image.

Step-by-Step Tutorial:
1️⃣ Open the app ‘InShot’
2️⃣ Create a new video
3️⃣ Select the 8 videos, your 21 photos and the black image (Select your photos/image by clicking ‘Photo’ at the top right)
4️⃣ Click the green ‘check-icon’ (Bottom right)
5️⃣ Trim your videos to 0.4 seconds
6️⃣ Trim the black image to 0.5 seconds and place it after each video
7️⃣ Trim all 21 photos to 0.2 seconds
8️⃣ Use this audio (for ‘Reels’: click the audio [camera.setup • Original Audio] > ‘Save Audio’ > Create Reel > Select your Video > Add Audio > Click ‘Saved’ > Select this Audio)

Video editing tutorial!🔥 In this tutorial, the app ‘InShot’ is being used. The app is available in the Google Play Store and the App Store.

If you want to recreate this video, you’ll need: one video and 27 images.

Step-by-Step Tutorial:
1️⃣ Open the app ‘InShot’
2️⃣ Create a new video
3️⃣ Select your video and your 27 images (Select your images by clicking ‘Photo’ at the top right)
4️⃣ Click the green ‘check-icon’ (Bottom right)
5️⃣ Trim your video to 4.4 seconds
6️⃣ Trim your 26 images to 0.4 seconds
7️⃣ Trim your last image to 0.2 seconds
8️⃣ Use this audio (for ‘Reels’: click the audio [camera.setup • Add 27 Photos] > ‘Save Audio’ > Create Reel > Select your Video > Add Audio > Click ‘Saved’ > Select this Audio)

One of the most important and difficult components of photography is lighting. Furthermore, it is one of the least well-known. The word “photography” has Greek roots and literally means “light drawing.” Beginners, on the other hand, frequently pick up their smartphone and start shooting without giving much thought to lighting.

What you need for a better lighting setup:

1. KEY LIGHT

A photographer will utilize the key light as the first and typically most essential light in a lighting setup. The main light’s job is to draw attention to the subject’s form and dimension.

2. FILL LIGHT

A fill light is a light used to lower the contrast of a scene to match the dynamic range of the recorded content

3. BACKLIGHT

Backlighting is placing the main light source behind the primary subject. Photographers utilize this method to produce dramatic lighting.
